---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import StackDiagram from "../../components/StackDiagram.astro";
import { loadLayers } from "../../lib/layers";

const layers = loadLayers();
---

<BaseLayout
  title="The Stack"
  description="Nine core layers and five cross-cutting meta-layers of the open-source AI stack. Click any layer to see what is in it."
>
  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-6 pt-16 pb-4">
    <p
      class="font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-[var(--color-text-subtle)] mb-4"
    >
      The Stack
    </p>
    <h1
      class="font-serif text-4xl md:text-5xl leading-tight tracking-tight text-[var(--color-text)] mb-6"
    >
      Nine layers, five cross-cuts
    </h1>
    <p
      class="text-lg text-[var(--color-text-muted)] leading-relaxed max-w-prose"
    >
      The open-source AI stack has nine layers in production-pipeline order
      (what gets built on top of what). It also has five cross-cutting
      meta-layers that observe or constrain the whole stack rather than
      sitting between two other layers. Click any layer for what is in it.
    </p>
  </section>

  <StackDiagram />

  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-6 my-16 prose">
    <h2>How to read this map</h2>
    <p>
      The nine core layers run in pipeline order: a chip
      (<a href="/stack/silicon">silicon</a>) goes somewhere (<a href="/stack/compute">compute</a>),
      gets fed something (<a href="/stack/data">data</a>) shaped by something else
      (<a href="/stack/training">training</a>) to produce
      <a href="/stack/weights">weights</a>, which a runtime
      (<a href="/stack/runtime">runtime</a>) serves to an agent
      (<a href="/stack/agents">agents</a>) that talks to other agents and tools
      via wire protocols (<a href="/stack/protocols">protocols</a>). The agent
      also reaches into a retrieval and memory store
      (<a href="/stack/retrieval-memory">retrieval and memory</a>) at call time.
    </p>
    <p>
      The cross-cutting meta-layers do not sit between two layers in the
      pipeline. They observe (<a href="/stack/evaluation">evaluation</a>),
      define (<a href="/stack/governance">governance</a>), trust-anchor
      (<a href="/stack/identity-trust">identity and trust</a>), constrain
      (<a href="/stack/safety-guardrails">safety and guardrails</a>), and shape
      the political framing
      (<a href="/stack/sovereignty-decentralization">sovereignty and decentralization primitives</a>).
    </p>
    <p>
      Each layer page has five views in one place: the editorial explainer of
      what the layer is, the living catalog of projects in it, the latest news
      at the layer, the grants flowing into it, and a curated reading list for
      going deeper. That five-in-one structure is what the rest of the
      open-AI web does not currently offer.
    </p>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
